# Token efficiency (strict)

## Before acting

- Read only files directly needed for the task — never bulk-read the repo
- Use targeted search (grep/glob) instead of opening large files whole
- Prefer reading 1 relevant file over 5 possibly-relevant files
- Do not re-read files already in context unless they changed

## During work

- No exploratory subagents or broad codebase scans for simple tasks
- No parallel reads "just in case" — batch only truly independent lookups
- Skip reading README, lockfiles, or config unless the task requires them
- Do not dump file contents in responses — cite line ranges only when needed
- Avoid repeating context the user already provided

## Output

- Short, direct answers — no preamble ("Great question!", "I'll help you…")
- No summarizing every file you opened
- No mermaid/ascii diagrams unless complexity demands it
- No optional follow-up lists — one clear next step if needed
- Code citations: smallest useful snippet, not whole files

## Tool discipline

- One lint pass on edited files only, not the whole project
- Do not run build unless verifying a fix or explicitly asked
- Do not create todos for ≤3 step tasks
- Do not write tests/docs unless requested

## When stuck

- Try one alternative approach before expanding scope
- Ask one focused question instead of investigating 10 files
